#compdef elton
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# robsimmons/l10 sml/frontend/elton.sml
# (**Standard ML language**; uses **stdlib
# `GetOpt`** — Standard ML Basis Library's CLI
# parser (`MLton.GetOpt` / `SML/NJ.GetOpt`), a
# port of the GHC Haskell `System.Console.GetOpt`
# port of the GNU getopt_long API.  Corpus's
# **first documented Standard ML CLI library**.
# Pivots from R308 _hiq (Hare stdlib getopt) into
# the Standard ML ecosystem):
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml line 1
#     (`structure Elton:> sig ... end = struct ...
#     end` — SML OPAQUE STRUCTURE with SIGNATURE.
#     SML's `structure NAME:> SIG = struct ... end`
#     is the MODULE SYSTEM: a named, namespaced
#     collection of types, values, and substructures
#     hidden behind a signature.  Distinct from
#     R301 Nim cligen's module (Nim package),
#     R302 Clojure babashka.cli (Clojure ns),
#     R306 Elixir Optimus (Elixir module).
#     SML's `:>` is the OPAQUE SEAL — clients can't
#     see internal types; sister to OCaml's `module
#     M : SIG = struct ... end`)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml lines 16-21
#     (`datatype options = Verbose | Help |
#     Prefix of string | Sources of string |
#     Directory of string` — SML ALGEBRAIC DATA
#     TYPE.  `datatype` declares a sum type with
#     constructors `Verbose`, `Help` (NULLARY),
#     `Prefix`, `Sources`, `Directory` (each taking
#     ONE string).  The parsed option becomes a
#     TAGGED VALUE in this ADT.  Distinct from R305
#     C++ CLI11 (struct fields), R306 Elixir Optimus
#     (atom-keyed map), R307 Vala GLib (typed-flag
#     enum + bound-variable references), R308 Hare
#     getopt (anonymous tuple).  SML's approach:
#     PARSED OPTION IS A TAGGED VALUE IN AN ADT —
#     corpus's **first documented ADT-as-parsed-
#     value CLI pattern**)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml lines 23-39
#     (`val options: options GetOpt.opt_descr
#     list = [ ... ]` — SML POLYMORPHIC LIST of
#     `opt_descr` records.  `options GetOpt.opt_
#     descr` is the TYPE APPLICATION: `GetOpt`'s
#     `opt_descr` is PARAMETERIZED OVER the user's
#     option ADT (`options` here).  Each record
#     has FOUR fields: `short` (string of chars),
#     `long` (list of strings), `desc` (variant
#     describing arg-shape), `help` (string).
#     SML records use `{label = value, ...}`
#     syntax with COMMA SEPARATORS.  Distinct from
#     R301 Nim cligen (proc-signature), R306 Elixir
#     Optimus (keyword list), R307 Vala GLib
#     (struct-literal table), R308 Hare getopt
#     (tagged-union array).  SML's approach:
#     PARAMETERIC-RECORD-LIST — opt_descr is
#     GENERIC over the user's ADT)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml line 24
#     (`{short = "vV", long = ["verbose"], desc =
#     GetOpt.NoArg (fn () => Verbose), help =
#     "Print out signature and compiler messages."}`
#     — VERBOSE flag spec.  `short = "vV"` —
#     MULTI-LETTER SHORT FORM: BOTH `-v` AND `-V`
#     are accepted as the verbose flag (the
#     `short` field is a STRING — each character
#     is a separate short-flag alias).  Distinct
#     from R304 Ada `Define_Switch` (only one
#     short character per option), R307 Vala GLib
#     (single char in OptionEntry), R308 Hare
#     getopt (single char tuple field), R306
#     Elixir Optimus (single `short:` string).
#     SML's STRING-OF-CHARS-IS-MULTIPLE-SHORTS is
#     UNIQUE.  Corpus's **first documented multi-
#     character-short-flag-string CLI pattern**)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml line 26
#     (`desc = GetOpt.NoArg (fn () => Verbose)` —
#     `NoArg` constructor + THUNK that returns
#     the ADT tag.  When the flag is matched,
#     the thunk runs and produces the `Verbose`
#     ADT value.  Distinct from `ReqArg (Prefix,
#     "l10")` (takes a CONSTRUCTOR + PLACEHOLDER
#     NAME), `OptArg` (optional arg).  SML's
#     approach: `desc` is a TAGGED VARIANT
#     describing the arg-shape AND how to
#     construct the parsed value)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml lines 27-32
#     (REQUIRED-ARG flags:
#       `{short = "p", long = ["prefix"], desc =
#         GetOpt.ReqArg (Prefix, "l10"), help =
#         "Prefix for signatures, structures, and
#         files."}`
#       — `ReqArg (CTOR, PLACEHOLDER)` says: when
#       matched, take the next argv element,
#       apply the constructor `Prefix` to it,
#       producing a `Prefix "value"` tagged
#       value.  `"l10"` is the placeholder shown
#       in help text)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml lines 62-66
#     (`val (opts, files) = GetOpt.getOpt
#       {argOrder = GetOpt.Permute, options =
#       options, errFn = errFn} args` —
#     GetOpt.getOpt INVOCATION returns a PAIR:
#     parsed `opts: options list` + leftover
#     POSITIONALS `files: string list`.  Distinct
#     from R304 Ada `Getopt(Config)` (mutates
#     aliased variables via Access pointers),
#     R307 Vala GLib `oc.parse(ref args)` (mutates
#     argv), R308 Hare `getopt::parse` (returns
#     command struct with .opts/.args).  SML's
#     approach: TUPLE RETURN VALUE — both halves
#     returned as a 2-tuple value)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml line 63
#     (`argOrder = GetOpt.Permute` — three argOrder
#     policies in SML GetOpt:
#       `Permute`  ← reorder argv so options precede
#                    positionals (default for
#                    GNU getopt long behaviour)
#       `RequireOrder` ← stop at first positional
#       `ReturnInOrder` ← treat positionals as
#                    `--` arguments and pass to
#                    handler
#     This is the SAME tri-state policy as Haskell's
#     `System.Console.GetOpt` because SML's GetOpt
#     is a PORT OF that Haskell library)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml lines 68-69
#     (`val (prefix, sources, dir) = foldr
#       processOpt ("l10", "l10.sources", OS.
#       FileSys.getDir ()) opts` — RIGHT-FOLD over
#     parsed options to thread state through.
#     SML's `foldr : ('a * 'b -> 'b) -> 'b -> 'a
#     list -> 'b` applies `processOpt` right-to-
#     left across the parsed `opts` list.
#     Distinct from R287 Nim parseopt (caller-
#     driven for-loop), R307 Vala GLib (bindings
#     mutated in-place by parser).  SML's approach:
#     FOLD-RIGHT THROUGH PARSED ADT LIST —
#     functional-style state threading)
#   sml/frontend/elton.sml line 53
#     (`val usageinfo = GetOpt.usageInfo {header
#       = "Usage: " ^ name ^ " [options] file.l10
#       ...\nOptions:", options = options} ^ "\n"`
#     — `GetOpt.usageInfo` generates the `--help`
#     text from the same options-list.  Takes a
#     RECORD `{header, options}` and returns a
#     formatted string)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# CLI surface (decoded from options-list in elton.sml):
#   -v / -V / --verbose       NoArg; verbose output (MULTI-SHORT)
#   -p PREFIX / --prefix=P    ReqArg; prefix for sigs/structs/files (default: l10)
#   -d DIR / --directory=D    ReqArg; output directory (default: cwd)
#   -h / --help               NoArg; show usage
#
# Positional: file.l10 ... (one or more L10 source files)
#
# elton is the FRONTEND BINARY of L10 (the L10
# Logic Programming Language) — generates SML
# source-code databases from `.l10` files for
# integration with SML projects.  Authored by Rob
# Simmons (formerly CMU; HOL prover & l10 author).
# 10 GH stars.  L10 itself compiles to SML code,
# so elton is the SML-CODE-GENERATING side of the
# language.  Sister tools: mlton (SML compiler,
# already in corpus; targets `elton-mlton.sml` as
# the binary entry point), smlnj (alternative SML
# compiler, in corpus).
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **Standard
# ML stdlib `GetOpt` structure** at elton.sml:23,
# 62 — corpus's **first documented Standard ML
# CLI library**.  SML's stdlib `GetOpt` is part
# of the SML Basis Library (available in MLton,
# SML/NJ, MLKit, Poly/ML, MoSML).  Implementation
# at `sml/basis-library/system/getopt.sml` in the
# MLton tree.  Originally PORTED FROM Haskell's
# `System.Console.GetOpt` (which itself is a port
# of GNU getopt_long).  Distinct from R270 Haskell
# `optparse-applicative` (newer applicative-style
# library), R287 Nim stdlib `parseopt` (token
# iterator, lower-level), R272 C POSIX getopt
# (single-byte short flags only).  SML's GetOpt
# is FUNCTIONAL-DESIGN: opaque parser, type-
# parameterized opt_descr, tuple-return.  Extends
# cross-language CLI taxonomy to FORTY-EIGHT
# library variants: Rust (6), Go (4), Python (3),
# Crystal 1 OptionParser (R269), Haskell (R270),
# OCaml (R271), C (R272), Java (R276),
# Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278), Dart (R279),
# Ruby (R280), Perl (R281), PHP (R282),
# Swift (R283), F# (R284), Lua (R285), C# (R286),
# Nim 1 parseopt (R287), Zig (R288), D (R289),
# Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294),
# Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296),
# SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300),
# Nim 2 cligen (R301), Clojure babashka.cli (R302),
# Gleam Glint (R303), Ada GNAT.Command_Line (R304),
# C++ CLI11 (R305), Elixir Optimus (R306), Vala
# GLib.OptionContext (R307), Hare stdlib getopt
# (R308), **Standard ML stdlib GetOpt** (R309 —
# NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 48 cross-
# language CLI library variants documented.
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **SML ADT-
# as-parsed-value CLI pattern** at elton.sml:16-21
# — `datatype options = Verbose | Help | Prefix
# of string | Sources of string | Directory of
# string`.  The parsed option becomes a TAGGED
# VALUE in this ADT.  Each flag/option PRODUCES a
# CONSTRUCTED ADT VALUE; the caller then pattern-
# matches the parsed `options list` to drive
# behaviour.  Distinct from R305 C++ CLI11 (struct
# fields bound by reference), R306 Elixir Optimus
# (atom-keyed map in the ParseResult struct), R307
# Vala GLib (typed-flag enum + bound-variable
# references), R308 Hare getopt (anonymous tuple
# of char + string).  SML's approach: PARSED
# OPTION IS A TAGGED VALUE IN A USER-DEFINED ADT
# — corpus's **first documented ADT-as-parsed-
# value CLI pattern**.  Sister to R270 Haskell
# optparse-applicative (which can also build into
# any value, but uses applicative composition
# rather than user-defined ADT).
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **SML
# parametric-record-list option specification** at
# elton.sml:23 — `val options: options GetOpt.opt_
# descr list = [...]`.  SML's `opt_descr` is a
# RECORD TYPE PARAMETERIZED OVER the user's option
# ADT.  The `options GetOpt.opt_descr` notation is
# SML's TYPE APPLICATION (postfix: type-arg comes
# BEFORE the type-constructor).  Each record has
# four labelled fields: `short` (string),
# `long` (list of strings), `desc` (variant), and
# `help` (string).  Distinct from R301 Nim cligen
# (proc-signature), R306 Elixir Optimus (keyword
# list), R307 Vala GLib (struct-literal table),
# R308 Hare getopt (tagged-union array).  SML's
# approach: PARAMETRIC-RECORD-LIST — `opt_descr`
# is GENERIC over the user's ADT.  Corpus's
# **first documented postfix-type-application CLI
# spec pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **SML
# multi-character-short-flag-string** at elton.sml:
# 24 — `short = "vV"`.  The `short` field is a
# STRING — EACH CHARACTER IS A SEPARATE SHORT-FLAG
# ALIAS.  Thus `-v` AND `-V` both match the same
# verbose flag.  Distinct from R304 Ada `Define_
# Switch` (only one short character per option),
# R307 Vala GLib (single char in OptionEntry),
# R308 Hare getopt (single char tuple field),
# R306 Elixir Optimus (single `short:` string).
# SML's STRING-OF-CHARS-IS-MULTIPLE-SHORTS is
# UNIQUE in the corpus.  Corpus's **first
# documented multi-character-short-flag-string
# CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **SML
# GetOpt.NoArg/ReqArg/OptArg desc constructors**
# at elton.sml:24-37 — the `desc` field is a
# tagged-variant:
#   `GetOpt.NoArg (fn () => Verbose)`        ← no-arg
#                                              flag; thunk
#                                              produces the
#                                              parsed value
#   `GetOpt.ReqArg (Prefix, "l10")`          ← required-arg
#                                              option;
#                                              CONSTRUCTOR
#                                              + placeholder
#                                              name
#   `GetOpt.OptArg (fn s => Prefix (...), "l10")`
#                                            ← optional-arg
#                                              (sml-getopt
#                                              variant)
# Each variant encodes BOTH the arg-shape AND how
# to construct the parsed value.  Distinct from
# R304 Ada postfix-marker (`-X:` / `-X?`), R307
# Vala GLib OptionArg enum, R308 Hare tuple-arity-
# discriminator.  Corpus's **first documented
# constructor-variant-encodes-arg-shape CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **SML
# GetOpt.Permute argOrder policy** at elton.sml:63
# — `argOrder = GetOpt.Permute` is the GNU-getopt-
# style default: REORDER argv so options precede
# positionals.  Three argOrder policies: `Permute`
# (default), `RequireOrder` (stop at first
# positional), `ReturnInOrder` (treat positionals
# as `--` args).  This SAME tri-state policy
# exists in R270 Haskell `System.Console.GetOpt`
# because SML's GetOpt is a PORT OF that Haskell
# library.  Distinct from R307 Vala GLib (no
# equivalent — always permutes), R308 Hare getopt
# (no equivalent — single mode).  Corpus's **first
# documented tri-state-argOrder-policy CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: elton uses **SML
# foldr through parsed-ADT-list state-threading**
# at elton.sml:68-69 — `val (prefix, sources, dir)
# = foldr processOpt ("l10", "l10.sources", OS.
# FileSys.getDir ()) opts`.  SML's `foldr` applies
# `processOpt` right-to-left across the parsed
# `opts` list, threading a tuple-of-state through.
# `processOpt` pattern-matches on each ADT
# constructor and updates the relevant tuple
# slot.  Distinct from R287 Nim parseopt (caller-
# driven for-loop), R307 Vala GLib (bindings
# mutated in-place by parser), R308 Hare (for-..-
# iteration with switch-case).  SML's approach:
# FOLD-RIGHT THROUGH PARSED ADT LIST — corpus's
# **first documented foldr-through-parsed-ADT
# CLI handling pattern**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_mlton` / `_smlnj` /
# `_mosml` / `_polyml` / `_mlkit` (SML compilers
# all in corpus; they have their own complex CLIs
# but most use ad-hoc CommandLine.arguments
# rather than stdlib GetOpt).  Skipped `_unison`
# (DUP with stock zsh).  Lean detour: probed
# `leanprover/verso` (339 stars but uses HANDWRITTEN
# indexed-inductive-type parsing — not Lean's
# `Cli` library; deferred), `argumentcomputer/
# yatima` (146 stars — `Cli` usage commented out
# in current revision), `argumentcomputer/ix` (73
# stars — `Cli` usage commented out), `hhu-adam/
# lean-i18n` (12 stars — uses Lean Cli but only as
# `lake exe i18n` target, not a standalone
# binary; deferred until a standalone-binary Cli-
# library example surfaces).  Standard ML probed:
# `diku-dk/sml-getopt` (6 stars, THE LIBRARY
# ITSELF — examples directory has demos but no
# real binary), `Sciumo/TL_System` (0 stars, niche),
# `bocchino/AppleCore` (6 stars, AppleCore
# assembler — uses GetOpt but smaller surface),
# `EESI/nbc` (1 star, Naive Bayes Classifier,
# narrow CLI).  Chose `robsimmons/l10/elton`: 10
# stars (L10 Logic Programming Language by Rob
# Simmons), 4 flags including a MULTI-CHARACTER-
# SHORT-FLAG-STRING (`"vV"` for `-v`/`-V`), full
# GetOpt pattern exercise (datatype ADT + opt_descr
# record list + NoArg/ReqArg constructors +
# usageInfo + getOpt returns tuple + foldr through
# parsed list), real binary distributed as part of
# the L10 toolchain.  Single source file makes
# extraction clean.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

# 4 flags decoded source-direct from `val options`
# at elton.sml:23-39.  Multi-letter `-v`/`-V`
# verbose alias (SML-specific multi-short).
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-v -V --verbose)'{-v,-V,--verbose}'[print out signature and compiler messages]' \
  '(-p --prefix)'{-p+,--prefix=}'[prefix for signatures, structures, and files (default: l10)]:prefix:' \
  '(-d --directory)'{-d+,--directory=}'[directory for file output (default: cwd)]:directory:_files -/' \
  '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show usage message and exit]' \
  '*:L10 source file:_files -g "*.l10"' && ret=0

return ret
